---
import BaseLayout from "../layouts/BaseLayout.astro";

export const prerender = true;
---

<BaseLayout
	title="About"
	description="Dr Fazeen Nasser is an emergency medicine clinician in East London who builds clinical AI products. Everything he's built started as a problem on shift."
>
	<div class="max-w-[720px] mx-auto px-6 py-24 md:py-32">

		<!-- Intro with photo placeholder -->
		<div class="flex flex-col sm:flex-row gap-10 sm:gap-14 items-start mb-20">
			<!-- Photo slot -->
			<div
				class="shrink-0 w-32 h-40 sm:w-36 sm:h-44 rounded-sm flex items-center justify-center"
				style="background: var(--bg-elev); border: 1px dashed var(--rule);"
				aria-label="Profile photo placeholder"
			>
				<span class="meta text-fg-subtle/50 text-[10px] text-center leading-5">
					Photo<br />here
				</span>
			</div>

			<!-- Intro text -->
			<div class="pt-1">
				<p class="section-label mb-3">Dr Fazeen Nasser</p>
				<h1 class="text-[2rem] font-semibold tracking-tight text-fg leading-tight mb-5">About</h1>
				<p class="text-[1.0625rem] text-fg-muted leading-[1.8]">
					Emergency medicine clinician in East London. I also build clinical AI products.
				</p>
				<p class="text-[1.0625rem] text-fg-muted leading-[1.8] mt-4">
					The two things are connected — everything I've built started as a problem I saw on shift.
				</p>
			</div>
		</div>

		<article class="prose">
			<h2>The work</h2>

			<p>
				I trained as a doctor in India, graduating from Kasturba Medical College in Manipal in 2019. I
				joined the medical operations and product team at DailyRounds in Bengaluru, where I spent two
				and a half years helping scale India's leading medical education platform from an early-stage
				startup to over half a million users. I led a cross-functional team of twenty medical editors,
				designed the flagship "Pearls" feature, and did the unglamorous day-to-day work of translating
				clinical workflow into product requirements.
			</p>

			<p>
				Between 2022 and 2023 I ran a small family practice in Kerala. It was paper-based when I
				arrived. I partnered with a fintech-backed EHR startup to install and configure a digital
				record system; within weeks the clinic was running on software that our staff actively
				preferred to the old ledgers. That experience — being the only person in a resource-limited
				clinic who understood both the medicine and the technology — shaped how I think about
				health-tech deployment.
			</p>

			<p>
				I moved to London in late 2023 to practise emergency medicine at Whipps Cross Hospital as
				part of Barts Health NHS Trust. I'm currently an ST3-equivalent trust-grade doctor in a busy
				adult A&E, covering the full range of undifferentiated presentations across resus, majors,
				and ambulatory care. I co-lead a departmental quality improvement project on mental health
				pathway compliance and I teach medical students and foundation doctors on shift.
			</p>

			<h2>The building</h2>

			<p>Alongside clinical work, I build things. Most of them clinical AI.</p>

			<p>
				I've been experimenting with machine learning for healthcare since 2018, when I trained a
				convolutional neural network in PyTorch to prioritise chest X-rays as a final-year student.
				In 2020 I placed second at the MIT COVID-19 Hackathon with a team building AI triage tools.
				In 2022 I launched NeurallyMed — an AI-powered PLAB exam preparation platform — which was
				acquired in 2023.
			</p>

			<p>
				I'm a founding engineer at two sister ventures, <strong>Peerr.io</strong> and
				<strong>Aiigent.io</strong>, working on secure, AI-powered tooling for clinical networking and
				workflow. On the side I build smaller things I need — an AI guidelines retrieval platform for
				the ED (<strong>Aide</strong>), a fitness and nutrition assistant for myself
				(<strong>Leanifi</strong>), a project microsite for the QIP I'm running at Whipps
				(<strong>qip.fazeen.dev</strong>). Some of these turn into products. Some stay personal tools.
				All of them start with a problem I saw on a shift.
			</p>

			<h2>What I care about</h2>

			<p>
				Most clinical AI projects fail not because the model is weak but because the implementation is
				weak. Poor workflow integration, weak governance, unclear accountability, thin evaluation. I
				want to do the opposite — ship things, evaluate them properly, write down what worked and what
				didn't so other people don't have to learn the same lessons from scratch.
			</p>

			<p>That's the thread.</p>

			<hr />

			<p>
				Available for collaborations in clinical AI deployment, digital health product consulting, and
				speaking on clinician-led technology development. <a href="/contact">Contact me</a>.
			</p>
		</article>
	</div>
</BaseLayout>
